06101nam a22008175i 9789633861295DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222017hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338612957 a10.1515/97896338612952doi  a(DE-B1597)633465  a(OCoLC)1338019411  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aUA646 7aPOL0110102bisacsh04a355/.0330422304aThe Long Détente :bChanging Concepts of Security and Cooperation in Europe, 1950s–1980s /ced. by Oliver Bange, Poul Villaume. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (370 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcronyms and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Long Perspectives On Détente -- tEast-West Conflict: Short Cold War and Long Détente -- tThe Long Détente and the Soviet Bloc, 1953–1983 -- tPart II. East-West Trade -- tSoviet Snowdrops in the Ice Age? -- tEuropean Long-Term Investments in Détente -- tPart III. The Inextractability Of External And Domestic Security -- tNo End to “Political Ideological Diversion” -- tNew Security Concepts and Transnational Party Networks, 1976–1983 -- tPart IV. Détente In Europe: Change In Perceptions -- tContinuity and Transformation -- tPerception of the Other: “Kremlinologists” and “Westerners” -- tPart V. Détente In Europe: Change In Diplomatic Framings -- tPathfinders and Perpetuators of Détente -- tOvercoming the Crisis of Détente, 1979−1983 -- tPart VI. The U.S. Story: From Cooperation To Confrontation And Back -- tLyndon B. Johnson and the Building of East-West Bridges -- tBetween Power Politics and Morality -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Editors and Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book presents pieces of evidence, which – taken together – lead to an argument that goes against the grain of the established Cold War narrative. The argument is that a “long détente” existed between East and West from the 1950s to the 1980s, that it existed and lasted for good (economic, national security, societal) reasons, and that it had a profound impact on the outcome of the conflict between East and West and the quintessentially peaceful framework in which this “endgame” was played. New, Euro-centered narratives are offered, including both West and East European perspectives. These contributions point to critical inconsistencies and inherent problems in the traditional U.S. dominated narrative of the “Victory in the Cold War.” The argument of a “long détente” does not need to replace the ruling American narrative. Rather, it can and needs to be augmented with European experiences and perceptions. After all, it was Europe – its peoples, societies, and states – that stood both at the ideological and military frontline of the conflict between East and West, and it was here that the struggle between liberalism and communism was eventually decided.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aNational security--Europe--History--20th century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  aCold War, Communism, Foreign relations, Great powers, Liberal democracy, National security.1 aBange, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBange, Oliver, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBékés, Csaba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFasanaro, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKieninger, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipkin, Mikhail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLippert, Werner D., econt